<h3>Types of events</h3>
<dl>
<dt><h4>Mutually exclusive events</h4></dt>
<dd>Mutually exclusive events can never occur at the <e>same time</e>. Joint probability for such events is always 0 (zero).</br>
Notice that <e>simultaneity</e> is the key.</br>
</dd>
</dl>
<dl>
<dt>Ex.</dt>
<dd>A coin toss, it cannot yield both head and tail at the same time.</br>However, consider a case of drawing a King or Heart card from a deck of 52 card, there is a possiblity that card could be a <i>King</i> of <i>Hearts</i>. </br>
So, both are not mutually exclusive events. </br>While on the other hand drawing a card which is both King and Queen is not possible. Thus, both become mutually exclusive events.</dd>
</dl>
</p>
<center>
    <img src="/images/exclusion.svg" height="160px" /></p>
    P(A∩B) = 0
    </br>And,</br>P(A∪B) = P(A) + P(B)
</center></p>
</p>
<dl>
<dt>Finally,</dt>
<dd>Rolling a <e>single</e> dice and observing 2 and an odd number is impossible. (Mutually exclusive events)</br>
Instead, if two dices are rolled. Would it be still impossible to observe the above outcome?</dd>
</dt>
</dl>
<h4>Independent events</h4>
These are the events that don't affect each other.</br>
<dl>
<dt>
The Probability of two <e>independent</e> events happening <e>together</e> is simply.</dt>
<dd>P(A∩B) = P(A) * P(B)</p></dd>
<dt>And</br>The probability of <e>either</e> of them happening</dt>
<dd>P(A∪B) = P(A) + P(B) - P(A∩B)</br>
Wondering, why subtract P(A∩B). Remember the previous example of King of Hearts case, it belonged to the two worlds of outcome when:</br>1. You draw a King</br>2. You draw a Heart</br>
We counted it twice, i.e. once in P(A) and another in P(B).
</br>Or in other way think that both outcomes got merged as they cannot happen individually so that has to be counted only once and not separately. Give it a thought and spend some time here. It might not be evident in one go, but you shall understand it.
</dd></p>
<dt>Ex.</dt>
<dd>
Consider rolling of two dices instead of one. Let event A be observing 2 on the first and B be observing an odd number on the second.</br>
P(A) = 1/6 and P(B) = 3/6</br>
P(A∩B) = P(A) * P(B) = 1/6 * 3/6 = 1/12</br>
P( observing 2 on first or observing odd number on second ) = P(A∪B) = P(A) + P(B) - P(A∩B) = 1/6 + 3/6 - 1/12 = 21/36.</p>
<i>One very important thing to note here is that both events A and B are not mutually exclusive. As both can occur at the same time.</i>
</dd>
</dt>
</dl>
<h4>Dependent events</h4>
When an occurance of one event affects the occurance of another, they are said to be dependent events.
<dl>
<dt><dd>
P(A∩B) = P(A) * P(B|A) = P(B) * P(A|B)
</br>And, P(A∪B) = P(A) + P(B) - P(A∩B)</br>
Where, P(B|A) = Probability of B given A is observed.</br>
Similarly, P(A|B) = Probability of A  given B is observed.
</dd></dt>
</dl>
<dl>
<dt>Ex.</dt>
<dd>Drawing two cards from a deck of 52 cards such that first is a face card and second is a number card.</br>
Here, when the first card is draw p(face card) = 12/52</br> 
For second card no. of total choices is 51 from which favourable outcomes can be drawn, such that p(number card) = 40/51.</br>
The P(1st card is a face card and 2nd a number) = P(1st is a face card) * P(2nd is a no. card given 1st is a face card) = 12/15 * 40/51.
</dd>
</dt>
</dl>
We encounter something special here i.e., P(B|A) and P(A|B) identified as <e>conditional probabilities</e>.
</p>
<h3>Conditional probability</h3>
Probability of happening of an event A given that event B has <i>also</i> happened or observed.</p>
<center>
P(A|B) = P(A∩B) / P(B)</br>And similarly</br>
P(B|A) = P(A∩B) / P(A)</p>
</center>
Universe changes and favourable outcomes are evaluated relative to this new universe.</p>
